The Ochi clan is said to have originated in {{ill|Ochi-go|ja|越智郷}} (modern {{ill|Kokubu, Imabari|ja|今治市国分}}). During the late 4th century, the establishment of the {{ill|Kuni no miyatsuko|ja|国造}} system by the Yamato court led to the creation of five Kuni no miyatsuko in western Ehime, including the Ochi clan. The clan’s founder is traditionally considered {{ill|Ochinomikoto|ja|小致命}}, grandson of Ōshinkawa no Mikoto of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏}} lineage (『{{ill|Kuni no miyatsuko no Hongi|ja|国造本紀}}』). According to the 『{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録}}』, Ochi no Atai (later Ochi Sukune) was a {{ill|Divine lineage|ja|神別}} clan descending from {{ill|Nigi Hayahi no Mikoto|ja|饒速日命}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digital.archives.go.jp/file/1256162.html|title=Shinsen Shōjiroku|website=National Archives of Japan|accessdate=2024-03-10}}</ref>

