'''Ochi clan''' (越智氏) refers to a {{ill|clan|ja|氏族|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with the name "Ochi."

The Ochi clan was one of the prominent {{ill|Gōzoku|lt=local ruling clans|ja|豪族|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in ancient {{ill|Japan|ja|日本|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, originating in {{ill|Iyo Province|ja|伊予国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (present-day {{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).<ref name="kot">{{cite kotobank|word=越智氏|author=山内 譲|encyclopedia=改訂新版 {{ill|World Encyclopedia|ja|世界大百科事典|qq=draft|qq=draft}}|accessdate=2024-03-10}}</ref> Some theories link the clan's origins to its association with the development of the {{ill|Nankaidō|ja|南海道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} region, but this connection remains unverified.

== Overview ==

The Ochi clan is said to have originated in {{ill|Ochi-go|ja|越智郷|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (modern {{ill|Kokubu, Imabari|ja|今治市国分|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). During the late 4th century, the establishment of the {{ill|Kuni no miyatsuko|ja|国造|qq=draft|qq=draft}} system by the Yamato court led to the creation of five Kuni no miyatsuko in western Ehime, including the Ochi clan. The clan’s founder is traditionally considered {{ill|Ochinomikoto|ja|小致命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, grandson of Ōshinkawa no Mikoto of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} lineage (『{{ill|Kuni no miyatsuko no Hongi|ja|国造本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』). According to the 『{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』, Ochi no Atai (later Ochi Sukune) was a {{ill|Divine lineage|ja|神別|qq=draft|qq=draft}} clan descending from {{ill|Nigihayahi|ja|饒速日命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digital.archives.go.jp/file/1256162.html|title=Shinsen Shōjiroku|website=National Archives of Japan|accessdate=2024-03-10}}</ref>

During the early 8th century, the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}} reorganized the administrative divisions into fourteen districts, designating the former Ochi Kuni no Miyatsuko territory as "Ochi District." The district became the site of Iyo’s {{ill|provincial government|ja|国府|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|provincial temple|ja|国分寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Archaeological investigations near Kokubu have suggested a connection between the Ochi clan and the provincial government, but conclusive evidence is lacking.

The earliest recorded figure of the Ochi clan is Ochi no Atai, a district governor of Ochi District. According to the 『{{ill|Nihon Ryōiki|ja|日本霊異記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』, he was captured during the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft}} but returned safely thanks to the blessings of {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, to whom he later dedicated a temple. While the location of this ancient temple remains unknown, it reflects an effort to reassert local authority through Buddhism.

In the history of Iyo, the first documented Ochi clan members were Ochi no Atai Asukamaro and Ochi no Atai Kunimaru, who were promoted in 767 ({{ill|Jingō-keiun|ja|神護景雲|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1) for their tribute offerings. Later, Ochi Mochitada received official recognition in 948 ({{ill|Tenryaku|ja|天暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2) for subduing pirates during the {{ill|Jōhei Tengyō War|ja|承平天慶の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Despite occasional mentions of the Ochi clan in historical records, the clan disappeared from Iyo’s political scene after Ochi Tamemori’s appointment as a military commissioner in 1002 ({{ill|Chōhō|ja|長保|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4).

== Legacy and Decline ==

The Ochi clan’s decline is marked by the increasing influence of the {{ill|Kōno clan|ja|河野氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Iyo Province. While sources like 『{{ill|Yoshōki|ja|予章記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』 provide genealogies linking the Ochi and Kōno clans, these accounts are often embellished with myths, such as tracing the Ochi lineage to Emperor Kōrei’s grandson. Such claims have been met with skepticism due to their lack of historical credibility.

According to the {{ill|Ōyamazumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社|1=Ōyamazumi Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in modern {{ill|Ōmishima, Imabari|ja|今治市大三島町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Ochi clan became the shrine’s hereditary priests, later adopting the surname {{ill|Mishima|ja|三島家|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Today, "Ochi" remains a common surname in Imabari City. Notably, during the early Meiji era, documents recorded political leader {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|ja|伊藤博文|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as "Ochi Sukune Hirobumi."

