During the early 8th century, the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}} reorganized the administrative divisions into fourteen districts, designating the former Ochi Kuni no Miyatsuko territory as "Ochi District." The district became the site of Iyo’s {{ill|provincial government|ja|国府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/provincial government|qq=}} and {{ill|provincial temple|ja|国分寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/provincial temple|qq=}}. Archaeological investigations near Kokubu have suggested a connection between the Ochi clan and the provincial government, but conclusive evidence is lacking.

The earliest recorded figure of the Ochi clan is Ochi no Atai, a district governor of Ochi District. According to the 『{{ill|Nihon Ryōiki|ja|日本霊異記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Ryōiki|qq=}}』, he was captured during the {{ill|Battle of Baekgang|ja|白村江の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Baekgang|qq=}} but returned safely thanks to the blessings of {{ill|Kannon|ja|観音菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kannon|qq=}}, to whom he later dedicated a temple. While the location of this ancient temple remains unknown, it reflects an effort to reassert local authority through Buddhism.

In the history of Iyo, the first documented Ochi clan members were Ochi no Atai Asukamaro and Ochi no Atai Kunimaru, who were promoted in 767 ({{ill|Jingō-keiun|ja|神護景雲|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jingō-keiun|qq=}} 1) for their tribute offerings. Later, Ochi Mochitada received official recognition in 948 ({{ill|Tenryaku|ja|天暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenryaku|qq=}} 2) for subduing pirates during the {{ill|Jōhei Tengyō War|ja|承平天慶の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōhei Tengyō War|qq=}}. Despite occasional mentions of the Ochi clan in historical records, the clan disappeared from Iyo’s political scene after Ochi Tamemori’s appointment as a military commissioner in 1002 ({{ill|Chōhō|ja|長保|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōhō|qq=}} 4).

== Legacy and Decline ==

The Ochi clan’s decline is marked by the increasing influence of the {{ill|Kōno clan|ja|河野氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōno clan|qq=}} in Iyo Province. While sources like 『{{ill|Yoshōki|ja|予章記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshōki|qq=}}』 provide genealogies linking the Ochi and Kōno clans, these accounts are often embellished with myths, such as tracing the Ochi lineage to Emperor Kōrei’s grandson. Such claims have been met with skepticism due to their lack of historical credibility.

According to the {{ill|Ōyamazumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社|1=Ōyamazumi Shrine|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamazumi Shrine|qq=}} in modern {{ill|Ōmishima, Imabari|ja|今治市大三島町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmishima, Imabari|qq=}}, the Ochi clan became the shrine’s hereditary priests, later adopting the surname {{ill|Mishima|ja|三島家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mishima|qq=}}. Today, "Ochi" remains a common surname in Imabari City. Notably, during the early Meiji era, documents recorded political leader {{ill|Itō Hirobumi|ja|伊藤博文|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itō Hirobumi|qq=}} as "Ochi Sukune Hirobumi."

