'''Ochi clan''' (越智氏) refers to a [[:en:Clan|clan]] with the name "Ochi."

The Ochi clan was one of the prominent [[:en:Gōzoku|local ruling clans]] in ancient [[:en:Japan|Japan]], originating in [[:en:Iyo Province|Iyo Province]] (present-day [[:en:Ehime Prefecture|Ehime Prefecture]]).<ref name="kot">{{cite kotobank|word=越智氏|author=山内 譲|encyclopedia=改訂新版 [[:en:Heibonsha World Encyclopedia|World Encyclopedia]]|accessdate=2024-03-10}}</ref> Some theories link the clan's origins to its association with the development of the [[:en:Nankaidō|Nankaidō]] region, but this connection remains unverified.

== Overview ==

The Ochi clan is said to have originated in {{ill|Ochi-go|ja|越智郷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochi-go|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (modern {{ill|Kokubu, Imabari|ja|今治市国分|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokubu, Imabari|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}). During the late 4th century, the establishment of the [[:en:Kuni no miyatsuko|Kuni no miyatsuko]] system by the Yamato court led to the creation of five Kuni no miyatsuko in western Ehime, including the Ochi clan. The clan’s founder is traditionally considered {{ill|Ochinomikoto|ja|小致命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ochinomikoto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, grandson of Ōshinkawa no Mikoto of the [[:en:Mononobe clan|Mononobe clan]] lineage (『{{ill|Kuni no miyatsuko no Hongi|ja|国造本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni no miyatsuko no Hongi|qq=|1=Kokuzo Hongi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q133833194}}』). According to the 『[[:en:Shinsen Shōjiroku|Shinsen Shōjiroku]]』, Ochi no Atai (later Ochi Sukune) was a {{ill|Shinbetsu|lt=Shinbetsu|lt=Divine lineage|ja|神別|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Divine lineage|qq=}} clan descending from {{ill|Nigihayahi|ja|饒速日命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nigihayahi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to ニギハヤヒ}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digital.archives.go.jp/file/1256162.html|title=Shinsen Shōjiroku|website=National Archives of Japan|accessdate=2024-03-10}}</ref>

During the early 8th century, the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] reorganized the administrative divisions into fourteen districts, designating the former Ochi Kuni no Miyatsuko territory as "Ochi District." The district became the site of Iyo’s [[:en:Kokufu|provincial government]] and [[:en:Provincial temple|provincial temple]]. Archaeological investigations near Kokubu have suggested a connection between the Ochi clan and the provincial government, but conclusive evidence is lacking.

The earliest recorded figure of the Ochi clan is Ochi no Atai, a district governor of Ochi District. According to the 『{{ill|Nihon Ryōiki|ja|日本霊異記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Ryōiki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 日本国現報善悪霊異記}}』, he was captured during the [[:en:Battle of Baekgang|Battle of Baekgang]] but returned safely thanks to the blessings of [[:en:Avalokiteśvara|Kannon]], to whom he later dedicated a temple. While the location of this ancient temple remains unknown, it reflects an effort to reassert local authority through Buddhism.

In the history of Iyo, the first documented Ochi clan members were Ochi no Atai Asukamaro and Ochi no Atai Kunimaru, who were promoted in 767 ([[:en:Jingo-keiun|Jingō-keiun]] 1) for their tribute offerings. Later, Ochi Mochitada received official recognition in 948 ([[:en:Tenryaku|Tenryaku]] 2) for subduing pirates during the [[:en:Tengyō no Ran|Jōhei Tengyō War]]. Despite occasional mentions of the Ochi clan in historical records, the clan disappeared from Iyo’s political scene after Ochi Tamemori’s appointment as a military commissioner in 1002 ([[:en:Chōhō (era)|Chōhō]] 4).

== Legacy and Decline ==

The Ochi clan’s decline is marked by the increasing influence of the {{ill|Kōno clan|ja|河野氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōno clan|qq=}} in Iyo Province. While sources like 『{{ill|Yoshōki|ja|予章記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshōki|qq=|1=Yoshōki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11371102}}』 provide genealogies linking the Ochi and Kōno clans, these accounts are often embellished with myths, such as tracing the Ochi lineage to Emperor Kōrei’s grandson. Such claims have been met with skepticism due to their lack of historical credibility.

According to the [[:en:Ōyamazumi Shrine|Ōyamazumi Shrine]] in modern {{ill|Ōmishima, Imabari|ja|今治市大三島町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmishima, Imabari|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, the Ochi clan became the shrine’s hereditary priests, later adopting the surname {{ill|Mishima|ja|三島家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mishima|qq=|1=Mishima|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q123407803}}. Today, "Ochi" remains a common surname in Imabari City. Notably, during the early Meiji era, documents recorded political leader [[:en:Itō Hirobumi|Itō Hirobumi]] as "Ochi Sukune Hirobumi."

